WHEN the cop pulled over the speeding car on the R72 in Port Alfred, the driver said he was late for work.Warrant Officer Tertius Neethling could never have guessed what he would find when he decided to take a look in the boot.Police spokeswoman Captain Mali Govender told Daily Sun Neethling found the carcasses of two bushbuck, a grey duiker and a porcupine. There was also a live dog in the boot. &ldquo;Then he heard sounds coming from a backpack in the boot. When he searched the bag he found a dead rabbit and a live grey duiker. He also found a spear, two knives, a spotlight with a large battery and two ropes behind the driver seat,&rdquo; she said.Three men, aged 57, 30 and 26, were arrested and face charges of illegal hunting and possession of endangered wild animals. &ldquo;The total value of the animals is R18 000. The driver was also issued with warnings by an inspector from the local SPCA for transporting a live dog in the boot and allowing the duiker to suffer. &ldquo;The duiker had to be put down by the SPCA.&rdquo;